const TOPICS = [
  {id:'t1',title:'Limits and Continuity',subject:'calculus',subjectLabel:'Calculus',difficulty:'beginner',animation:'limit',description:'Explore how functions behave as they approach specific values through interactive visualizations of the epsilon-delta definition.',theory:'A limit describes the value that a function approaches as the input approaches some value. For \\(\\lim_{x \\to a} f(x) = L \\), we can make \\(f(x)\\) arbitrarily close to \\(L\\) by taking \\(x\\) sufficiently close to \\(a\\).\n\nThe classic example is \\(\\lim_{x \\to 0} \\frac{\\sin x}{x} = 1\\), which can be visualized by watching the function values converge as \\(x \\to 0\\) from both sides.\n\nA function \\(f\\) is continuous at \\(a\\) if \\(\\lim_{x \\to a} f(x) = f(a)\\).',refs:['r1','r2','r5']},
  {id:'t2',title:'Derivatives and Tangent Lines',subject:'calculus',subjectLabel:'Calculus',difficulty:'intermediate',animation:'derivative',description:'Visualize the derivative as the slope of the tangent line, and see how it changes as you move along a curve.',theory:'The derivative of \\(f\\) at point \\(a\\) is defined as:\n\\[ f\'(a) = \\lim_{h \\to 0} \\frac{f(a+h) - f(a)}{h} \\]\n\nGeometrically, this represents the slope of the tangent line to the curve \\(y = f(x)\\) at the point \\((a, f(a))\\).\n\nAs you drag the point along the curve, observe how the tangent line rotates and the slope value changes. Where the slope is zero, the function has a local maximum or minimum.',refs:['r1','r2','r6']},
  {id:'t3',title:'Integration via Riemann Sums',subject:'calculus',subjectLabel:'Calculus',difficulty:'intermediate',animation:'riemann',description:'Watch Riemann sums converge to the exact integral as the number of rectangles increases toward infinity.',theory:'The definite integral \\(\\int_a^b f(x)\\,dx\\) is defined as the limit of Riemann sums:\n\\[ \\int_a^b f(x)\\,dx = \\lim_{n \\to \\infty} \\sum_{i=1}^{n} f(x_i^*) \\Delta x \\]\n\nwhere \\(\\Delta x = \\frac{b-a}{n}\\) and \\(x_i^*\\) is a sample point in each subinterval.\n\nAs \\(n\\) increases, the rectangular approximation converges to the exact area under the curve.',refs:['r1','r3','r7']},
  {id:'t4',title:'Taylor and Maclaurin Series',subject:'calculus',subjectLabel:'Calculus',difficulty:'advanced',animation:'taylor',description:'See how polynomial approximations build up to match complex functions term by term.',theory:'The Taylor series of \\(f\\) centered at \\(a\\) is:\n\\[ f(x) = \\sum_{n=0}^{\\infty} \\frac{f^{(n)}(a)}{n!}(x-a)^n \\]\n\nWhen \\(a = 0\\), this is called a Maclaurin series. For example:\n\\[ e^x = \\sum_{n=0}^{\\infty} \\frac{x^n}{n!} = 1 + x + \\frac{x^2}{2!} + \\frac{x^3}{3!} + \\cdots \\]\n\nMore terms yield better approximations within the radius of convergence.',refs:['r2','r4','r8']},
  {id:'t5',title:'Matrix Operations',subject:'linear-algebra',subjectLabel:'Linear Algebra',difficulty:'beginner',animation:'matrix',description:'Visualize how matrix multiplication transforms 2D space and understand the geometric meaning of matrix operations.',theory:'Matrix multiplication combines linear transformations. For a \\(2 \\times 2\\) matrix \\(A = \\begin{pmatrix} a & b \\\\ c & d \\end{pmatrix}\\), multiplying a vector \\(\\mathbf{v}\\) by \\(A\\) produces a new vector:\n\\[ A\\mathbf{v} = \\begin{pmatrix} ax + by \\\\ cx + dy \\end{pmatrix} \\]\n\nThe determinant \\(\\det(A) = ad - bc\\) measures how the transformation scales area. If \\(\\det(A) = 0\\), the transformation collapses space.',refs:['r5','r9','r10']},
  {id:'t6',title:'Eigenvalues and Eigenvectors',subject:'linear-algebra',subjectLabel:'Linear Algebra',difficulty:'advanced',animation:'matrix',description:'Discover how eigenvectors remain on their span during transformation while being scaled by eigenvalues.',theory:'An eigenvector of matrix \\(A\\) is a nonzero vector \\(\\mathbf{v}\\) such that:\n\\[ A\\mathbf{v} = \\lambda \\mathbf{v} \\]\n\nwhere \\(\\lambda\\) is the corresponding eigenvalue. To find eigenvalues, solve:\n\\[ \\det(A - \\lambda I) = 0 \\]\n\nEigenvectors reveal the natural axes of a linear transformation — directions that only get scaled, not rotated.',refs:['r5','r9','r11']},
  {id:'t7',title:'Linear Transformations in 2D',subject:'linear-algebra',subjectLabel:'Linear Algebra',difficulty:'intermediate',animation:'matrix',description:'Explore rotations, reflections, shears, and scaling as matrix transformations of the plane.',theory:'Every linear transformation \\(T: \\mathbb{R}^2 \\to \\mathbb{R}^2\\) can be represented by a \\(2 \\times 2\\) matrix. Common transformations include:\n\nRotation by \\(\\theta\\): \\(\\begin{pmatrix} \\cos\\theta & -\\sin\\theta \\\\ \\sin\\theta & \\cos\\theta \\end{pmatrix}\\)\n\nReflection across x-axis: \\(\\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 \\\\ 0 & -1 \\end{pmatrix}\\)\n\nShear: \\(\\begin{pmatrix} 1 & k \\\\ 0 & 1 \\end{pmatrix}\\)',refs:['r5','r10','r11']},
  {id:'t8',title:'Kinematics and Projectile Motion',subject:'physics',subjectLabel:'Physics',difficulty:'beginner',animation:'harmonic',description:'Visualize projectile trajectories with adjustable initial velocity, angle, and gravitational acceleration.',theory:'Projectile motion decomposes into horizontal and vertical components:\n\\[ x(t) = v_0 \\cos\\theta \\cdot t \\]\n\\[ y(t) = v_0 \\sin\\theta \\cdot t - \\frac{1}{2}g t^2 \\]\n\nThe trajectory forms a parabola. Maximum range occurs at \\(\\theta = 45°\\) (in vacuum). Maximum height is:\n\\[ h_{max} = \\frac{v_0^2 \\sin^2\\theta}{2g} \\]',refs:['r12','r13','r14']},
  {id:'t9',title:'Simple Harmonic Motion',subject:'physics',subjectLabel:'Physics',difficulty:'intermediate',animation:'harmonic',description:'Observe spring-mass oscillations and explore how mass, spring constant, and damping affect the motion.',theory:'A mass on a spring follows:\n\\[ m\\ddot{x} + c\\dot{x} + kx = 0 \\]\n\nUndamped (\\(c=0\\)): \\(x(t) = A\\cos(\\omega t + \\phi)\\) where \\(\\omega = \\sqrt{k/m}\\)\n\nUnderdamped (\\(c < 2\\sqrt{km}\\)): oscillations with exponentially decaying amplitude.\n\nThe energy oscillates between kinetic and potential forms.',refs:['r12','r14','r15']},
  {id:'t10',title:'Wave Mechanics and Superposition',subject:'physics',subjectLabel:'Physics',difficulty:'intermediate',animation:'fourier',description:'See how waves combine through superposition and understand standing wave patterns.',theory:'The wave equation:\n\\[ \\frac{\\partial^2 y}{\\partial t^2} = v^2 \\frac{\\partial^2 y}{\\partial x^2} \\]\n\nSolutions include traveling waves \\(y = A\\sin(kx - \\omega t)\\). By superposition, two waves traveling in opposite directions create standing waves:\n\\[ y = 2A\\sin(kx)\\cos(\\omega t) \\]\n\nNodes occur where \\(\\sin(kx) = 0\\) and antinodes where \\(|\\sin(kx)| = 1\\).',refs:['r12','r13','r16']},
  {id:'t11',title:'Electromagnetic Wave Propagation',subject:'physics',subjectLabel:'Physics',difficulty:'advanced',animation:'fourier',description:'Visualize the coupled electric and magnetic fields of an EM wave propagating through space.',theory:'From Maxwell\'s equations, EM waves satisfy:\n\\[ \\nabla^2 \\mathbf{E} = \\mu_0 \\epsilon_0 \\frac{\\partial^2 \\mathbf{E}}{\\partial t^2} \\]\n\nThe wave speed is \\(c = 1/\\sqrt{\\mu_0 \\epsilon_0} \\approx 3 \\times 10^8\\) m/s.\n\n\\(\\mathbf{E}\\) and \\(\\mathbf{B}\\) fields oscillate perpendicular to each other and to the direction of propagation, with \\(E = cB\\).',refs:['r13','r16','r17']},
  {id:'t12',title:'First-Order ODEs',subject:'differential-equations',subjectLabel:'Differential Equations',difficulty:'intermediate',animation:'derivative',description:'Visualize slope fields and solution curves for first-order differential equations.',theory:'A first-order ODE has the form:\n\\[ \\frac{dy}{dx} = f(x, y) \\]\n\nA slope field displays short line segments with slope \\(f(x,y)\\) at each grid point. Solution curves follow these slopes.\n\nFor separable equations: \\(\\frac{dy}{dx} = g(x)h(y)\\), we integrate:\n\\[ \\int \\frac{1}{h(y)}\\,dy = \\int g(x)\\,dx \\]',refs:['r6','r18','r19']},
  {id:'t13',title:'Second-Order Linear ODEs',subject:'differential-equations',subjectLabel:'Differential Equations',difficulty:'advanced',animation:'harmonic',description:'Explore the phase portraits and time-domain solutions of second-order linear ODEs.',theory:'The general form:\n\\[ a\\ddot{x} + b\\dot{x} + cx = f(t) \\]\n\nThe characteristic equation \\(ar^2 + br + c = 0\\) determines behavior:\n- Two real roots: overdamped\n- Repeated root: critically damped\n- Complex roots: underdamped oscillation\n\\[ r = \\frac{-b \\pm \\sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a} \\]',refs:['r6','r18','r20']},
  {id:'t14',title:'Convergence Tests for Series',subject:'sequences-series',subjectLabel:'Sequences & Series',difficulty:'intermediate',animation:'limit',description:'Visualize partial sums of series and determine convergence through interactive exploration.',theory:'Key convergence tests:\n\nComparison Test: If \\(0 \\leq a_n \\leq b_n\\) and \\(\\sum b_n\\) converges, then \\(\\sum a_n\\) converges.\n\nRatio Test: If \\(L = \\lim_{n \\to \\infty} |a_{n+1}/a_n|\\), the series converges if \\(L < 1\\), diverges if \\(L > 1\\).\n\nIntegral Test: If \\(f\\) is positive and decreasing, \\(\\sum f(n)\\) and \\(\\int_1^{\\infty} f(x)\\,dx\\) share convergence behavior.',refs:['r4','r8','r21']},
  {id:'t15',title:'Fourier Series Decomposition',subject:'sequences-series',subjectLabel:'Sequences & Series',difficulty:'advanced',animation:'fourier',description:'Build up complex periodic functions from simple sine and cosine components.',theory:'A periodic function \\(f(x)\\) with period \\(2\\pi\\) can be expressed as:\n\\[ f(x) = \\frac{a_0}{2} + \\sum_{n=1}^{\\infty} \\left[ a_n \\cos(nx) + b_n \\sin(nx) \\right] \\]\n\nwhere:\n\\[ a_n = \\frac{1}{\\pi}\\int_{-\\pi}^{\\pi} f(x)\\cos(nx)\\,dx, \\quad b_n = \\frac{1}{\\pi}\\int_{-\\pi}^{\\pi} f(x)\\sin(nx)\\,dx \\]\n\nFor a square wave, only odd harmonics contribute: \\(b_n = \\frac{4}{n\\pi}\\) for odd \\(n\\).',refs:['r4','r8','r22']},
  {id:'t16',title:'Vector Fields and Flow',subject:'physics',subjectLabel:'Physics',difficulty:'advanced',animation:'vectorfield',description:'Visualize how vector fields dictate the movement of particles through space, from swirling vortices to gravitational sinks.',theory:'A vector field assigns a vector to every point in space. For a 2D field \\(\\mathbf{F}(x, y) = P(x,y)\\mathbf{i} + Q(x,y)\\mathbf{j}\\), we can visualize the flow by drawing arrows at grid points.\n\nCommon fields include:\n- Rotation: \\(\\mathbf{F} = -y\\mathbf{i} + x\\mathbf{j}\\)\n- Sink: \\(\\mathbf{F} = -x\\mathbf{i} - y\\mathbf{j}\\)\n- Saddle: \\(\\mathbf{F} = x\\mathbf{i} - y\\mathbf{j}\\)\n\nThe divergence \\(\\nabla \\cdot \\mathbf{F} = \\frac{\\partial P}{\\partial x} + \\frac{\\partial Q}{\\partial y}\\) tells us if fluid is expanding or compressing.',refs:['r12','r13']},
  {id:'t17',title:'The Double Pendulum & Chaos',subject:'physics',subjectLabel:'Physics',difficulty:'advanced',animation:'doublependulum',description:'Witness chaos theory in action. A tiny change in the starting angle creates a completely unpredictable path over time.',theory:'A double pendulum consists of one pendulum attached to the end of another. Despite being governed by simple classical mechanics, it exhibits extreme sensitivity to initial conditions—the hallmark of chaos.\n\nThe equations of motion are derived from the Lagrangian \\(L = T - V\\) and result in a pair of coupled, highly nonlinear second-order ODEs.\n\nBecause the system is chaotic, long-term prediction is impossible. A difference of 0.001 radians in the initial angle leads to completely divergent trajectories after just a few seconds.',refs:['r14','r15']}
];

